Let $O$ be the center of circle $P$, and let $R$ be the center of circle $Q$.  Let $X$ be the point where circle $P$ is tangent to $\overline{AC}$, and let $Y$ be the point where circle $Q$ is tangent to $\overline{BC}$.  Let $Z$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $R$ to $\overline{BC}$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, O, P, Q, X, Y, Z;

A = (0,100);
B = (-28,0);
C = (28,0);
O = (28,16);
P = (O + reflect(B,C)*(O))/2;
Q = (P + reflect(B,C)*(P))/2;
X = foot(O,A,C);
Y = foot(Q,B,C);
Z = foot(R,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(Circle(O,16));
draw(Circle(Q,abs(Q - Y)));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$O$", O, NE);
label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, N);
label("$X$", X, SE);
label("$Y$", Y, S);
label("$Z$", Z, S);
[/asy]

Since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, the altitude from $A$ bisects $\overline{BC}$, so $BC/2 = 28$.  Also, since $P$ is tangent to $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{BC}$, $OX = 16$ and $OP = 28$.  Then by the Pythagorean Theorem on right triangle $OPX$, we have $PX = \sqrt{OP^2 - OX^2} = \sqrt{28^2 - 16^2} = 20\sqrt{3}$.

Since $Q$ is tangent to $\overline{BC}$ and $\overline{AB}$, $RZ = r$ and $RQ = 28 + r$, where $r$ is the radius of circle $Q$.  Also, $PQ = 20\sqrt{3} + r$.  Then by the Pythagorean Theorem on right triangle $RQP$, we have $(20\sqrt{3} + r)^2 = r^2 + (28 + r)^2$.  Expanding and simplifying, we get $400 \cdot 3 = 56r + 784$, so $r = \frac{416}{56} = \frac{52}{7}$.

Therefore, the radius of circle $Q$ is $7 - \frac{52}{7} = \boxed{5}$.

